# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gpon-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] Passive optical networks are used for the *fibre-to-the-home* or *fibre-to-the-premises* last mile with splitters that connect each central transmitter to many subscribers.
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] The 10 Gbit/s shared capacity is the downstream speed broadcast to all users connected to the same PON, and the 2.5 Gbit/s upstream speed uses multiplexing techniques to prevent data frames from interfering with each other.
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] Each user has a network device that converts between the optical signals and the signals used in building wiring, such as Ethernet and wired analogue plain old telephone service.
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] XGS-PON is a related technology that can deliver upstream and downstream (symmetrical) speeds of up to 10 Gbit/s (gigabits per second), first approved in 2016 as G.9807.1.
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] XGS-PON uses time division multiplexing (TDM) and time division multiple access (TDMA).
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] ITU-T G.987 is the standard for 10G-PON.
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] Asymmetric 10G-PON is specified as XG-PON1: 10 Gbit/s downstream and 2.5 Gbit/s upstream (nominal line rate of 9.95328 Gbit/s downstream and 2.48832 Gbit/s upstream).
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] Symmetric 10G-PON is also proposed as XG-PON2 with 10 Gbit/s upstream, but would require more expensive burst-mode lasers on optical network terminals (ONTs) to deliver the upstream transmission speed.
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] Framing is "G-PON like" but uses different wavelengths from G-PON (using a WDM to separate them) so that G-PON subscribers can be upgraded to 10G-PON incrementally while GPON users continue on the original optical line terminal (OLT).
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] This compares to the IEEE 802.3av standard for 10G-EPON based on Ethernet, which has standardised upstream rates of both 1 Gbit/s and 10 Gbit/s.
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] The 10 gigabit PON wavelengths (1577 nm down / 1270 nm up) differ from GPON and EPON (1490 nm down /1310 nm up), allowing it to coexist on the same fibre with either of the gigabit PONs.
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] ITU-T Recommendation G.987 is a family that defines this access network standard (referred to as XG-PON).
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] There is also a companion ITU-T standard defining a management and control interface for administering optical network units, referred to by the G.987 recommendations.
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] The optical network unit (ONU) supplies network services from the PON to customer premises, connecting customer-premises equipment such as a home gateway or office firewall.
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] An optical network terminal (ONT) is an ONU that functions as a demarcation point servicing a single subscriber; e.g., a dwelling or office.
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] The ONU receives the downstream data from the Internet or private networks, and also uses time slots allocated by the OLT to send the upstream traffic in burst-mode.
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] TDMA time slots prevent collisions with upstream traffic from other users sharing the same physical PON.
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] Fibre-to-the-cell site is another emerging application, but has extra synchronisation requirements.
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] A specialised cellular backhaul unit (CBU) can provide PON access for cellular networks.
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] The OLT (optical line terminal) connects the PON to aggregated backhaul uplinks, allocates time slots for ONUs and ONTs to transmit upstream data, and transmits shared downstream data in broadcast-mode over the PON to users.
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] Since 10GPON is designed to coexist with GPON devices, migration to a 10GPON capability could be done by upgrading the OLT and then migrating individual ONUs as needed.
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] Normally the OLT is on a card that slots into an OLT chassis at the central office (CO), which uses special uplink cards for Ethernet backhaul to the telecommunications provider's network and internet.
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] Uplink cards on access equipment will likely use multiple Ethernet interfaces, although it remains to be seen what uplink speeds manufacturers will offer to support 10GPON access.
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] Locating OLTs in outside plant cabinets may be an option for reach extension as a way to minimise the number of central offices covering low population density areas.
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] ITU and IEEE are planning for convergence of their specifications at the physical layer in 10G that would allow for the shared chips, optics and hardware platforms, thus driving cost reductions for hardware manufacturers.
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] PON optical distribution networks use single-mode optical fibre in the outside plant, optical splitters and optical distribution frames, duplexed so that both upstream and downstream share the same fibre on separate wavelengths.
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] 10G-PON is no exception with reach similar to previous standards but supporting a higher split ratio of 128 users per PON, or more using reach extenders/amplifiers.
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] Optical splitters creating a point to multipoint topology are also the same technology as those used by other PON systems.
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] This means any PON network should be upgradable by changing the ONT and OLT terminals at each end, with no change to the fibre itself unless different connectors are chosen.
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] "An Optical Distribution Network (ODN) being installed today will likely need to support four or more generations of PON over its expected 30–40 year life...
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] The fibre should enable maximum flexibility to support any potential new PON technology, be protected with proven, reliable cabling making it easy to install and reliable, and be joined by advanced, low labor and low loss connectivity.
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] In an effort to extend the reach with support for 128 subscribers, the standard supports a range of optical budgets from 29 dB to 31 dB.
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] A draft update to the standard is expected to further extend this to 33 dB and 35 dB budget classifications.
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] A PON with a 35 dB optical budget could span 25 km or more and be shared among 128 subscribers.
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] XGS-PON also supports split ratios of up to 1:128.
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] Some ONTs can receive a broad range of optical spectrum from 1480 nm to 1580 nm, so making the 10G-PON downstream signal visible to G-PON receivers.
[src:gpon-deep/10g-pon] As a result, ONTs must block the unwanted downstream signals with a wavelength blocking filter (WBF), a small passive optical device.
[src:gpon-deep/gigabit-passive-optical-network] ITU-T **G.984** is the series of standards that define the architecture and operation of gigabit-per-second–capable passive optical network (**GPON**).
[src:gpon-deep/gigabit-passive-optical-network] It is commonly used to implement the link to the customer (the *last kilometre*, or *last mile*) of fiber-to-the-premises (FTTP) services, using a point-to-multipoint design.
[src:gpon-deep/gigabit-passive-optical-network] GPON supporting a shared bandwidth of downstream data rates of up to 2.4 Gbit/s and normally upstream rates of up to 1.2 Gbit/s.
[src:gpon-deep/gigabit-passive-optical-network] GPON uses passive optical network (PON) is a fiber-optic access architecture in which a single optical fiber from a central location is shared by multiple end users through one or more passive optical splitters in series (cascaded).
[src:gpon-deep/gigabit-passive-optical-network] Unlike traditional point-to-point fiber connections, PON systems distribute optical signals from an optical line terminal (OLT) to many optical network units (ONUs) or optical network terminals (ONTs) without requiring active electronic equipment in the distribution network.
[src:gpon-deep/gigabit-passive-optical-network] The absence of powered components between the central location and subscribers reduces infrastructure costs, simplifies maintenance, and increases reliability.
[src:gpon-deep/gigabit-passive-optical-network] In a PON architecture, downstream data is broadcast from the optical line terminal (OLT) to all connected optical network units (ONUs), while upstream data is coordinated using time-division multiple access to prevent signal collisions.
[src:gpon-deep/gigabit-passive-optical-network] Passive splitters divide optical signals across multiple fibers, typically serving 16 to 64 subscribers from a single fiber feeder.
[src:gpon-deep/gigabit-passive-optical-network] The standard specifies transmission convergence layer, physical layer requirements, management protocols, and service encapsulation for high-speed fiber access networks.
[src:gpon-deep/gigabit-passive-optical-network] GPON puts requirements on the optical medium and the hardware used to access it, and defines the manner in which Ethernet frames are converted to an optical signal, as well as the parameters of that signal.
[src:gpon-deep/gigabit-passive-optical-network] Unlike the EPON standard, which has a much simpler topology, GPON encapsulates Ethernet packets into virtual GPON encapsulation method (GEM) ports, TCONT queues and VLANIDs via OMCI.
[src:gpon-deep/gigabit-passive-optical-network] The exact kind of fiber cable and connectors to use is undefined but is broadly using OS2 cable with SC/APC connectors.
[src:gpon-deep/gigabit-passive-optical-network] GPON systems require precise timing and clock synchronization to ensure collision-avoidance in upstream transmission in the time-division multiple access (TDMA) from multiple optical network units (ONUs).
[src:gpon-deep/gigabit-passive-optical-network] The optical line terminal (OLT) provides the primary timing reference for the network, distributing timing information through the downstream signal (every 125µs).
[src:gpon-deep/gigabit-passive-optical-network] Optical network units (ONUs) recover the clock from the received downstream data stream and use it to align their upstream transmissions according to time slots (every 125µs) assigned by the dynamic bandwidth allocation mechanism defined in the transmission convergence layer.
[src:gpon-deep/gigabit-passive-optical-network] Attenuation classes in GPON define the allowable optical loss budget between the OLT and the ONU, ensuring reliable operation over a passive optical distribution network with varying fiber lengths and splitter configurations.
[src:gpon-deep/gigabit-passive-optical-network] The power-levelling mechanism in GPON is used to control the optical transmit power of the ONUs in the upstream direction.
[src:gpon-deep/gigabit-passive-optical-network] In a PON, multiple ONUs share the same optical distribution network and transmit bursts of upstream data toward the central OLT.
[src:gpon-deep/gigabit-passive-optical-network] Because ONUs may be located at different distances from the OLT and have different optical path losses, the received optical power at the OLT can vary significantly.
[src:gpon-deep/gigabit-passive-optical-network] The power-levelling mechanism allows the ONUs transmitter to adjust its launched optical power to compensate for these variations, ensuring that upstream bursts arrive at the OLT within an acceptable dynamic range.
[src:gpon-deep/gigabit-passive-optical-network] The mechanism operates by defining different ONUs transmit power levels and corresponding detection thresholds at the central OLT During operation, the central OLT measures the received optical power from each ONU and determines whether the power level falls within the desired operating window.
[src:gpon-deep/gigabit-passive-optical-network] If necessary, the OLT sends PLOAM *Change_power_level* message, the ONU adjusts its transmit power to maintain stable reception and prevent receiver overload or insufficient signal levels.
[src:gpon-deep/gigabit-passive-optical-network] In contrast to ADSL technology, which deteriorates as the distance between the central office and the household rises, with severe signal loss beyond 3km, all customers may enjoy high-speed network access within the 16km range of a fiber central office.
[src:gpon-deep/gigabit-passive-optical-network] The first version of GPON was ratified in 2003.
[src:gpon-deep/gigabit-passive-optical-network] Since then, it has been expanded upon and revised several times.
[src:gpon-deep/gigabit-passive-optical-network] As of July 2018, G.984.5 is currently being revised.
[src:gpon-deep/gigabit-passive-optical-network] The GPON OMCI recommendation G.984.4 draws on G.983.2, which defines the BPON management model.
[src:gpon-deep/gigabit-passive-optical-network] However, G.984.4 removed all references to ATM.
[src:gpon-deep/gigabit-passive-optical-network] G.988 is a stand-alone OMCI recommendation and supersedes G.984.4 except for GPON specifics that are not defined in G.988.
[src:gpon-deep/gigabit-passive-optical-network] Future work on the PON management model is expected to appear only in the GPON space.
[src:gpon-deep/gigabit-passive-optical-network] Security issues in the G.984 standard series include the possibility of eavesdropping on upstream traffic, replay attacks, PLOAM messages that are not integrity protected and denial of service to other subscribers on the same link.
[src:gpon-deep/ng-pon2] A passive optical network is a last mile, fibre-to-the-x telecommunications network that broadcasts data through fibre optic cables.
[src:gpon-deep/ng-pon2] PONs are managed by passive optics such as unpowered splitters and filters, offering high reliability and low cost compared to active networks.
[src:gpon-deep/ng-pon2] The PON data stream is generally converted to a more traditional service such as Ethernet and Wi-Fi at the subscriber's location.
[src:gpon-deep/ng-pon2] NG-PON2 is compatible with existing PON fibre by replacing optical line terminal (OLT) at the central office, and the optical network unit (ONU) near each end-user.
[src:gpon-deep/ng-pon2] Unique to this standard is the use of both active filters and tunable lasers in the ONU.
[src:gpon-deep/ng-pon2] From 2019 until 2021 a series of new Recommendations under the header Higher Speed PON (G.9804 series) was released intended as successors to NG-PON2.
[src:gpon-deep/ng-pon2] Wavelength allocations include 1524 nm to 1544 nm in the upstream direction and 1596 nm to 1602 nm in the downstream direction.
[src:gpon-deep/ng-pon2] The architecture calls for time- and wavelength-division multiplexing (**TWDM**) in the upstream and downstream directions.
[src:gpon-deep/ng-pon2] Wavelength-division multiplexing is provided in the downstream direction by combining light from four fixed wavelength OLT lasers with a wavelength mux.
[src:gpon-deep/ng-pon2] The light is then filtered at each ONU with an actively tunable filter that passes only the desired downstream wavelength to its receiver.
[src:gpon-deep/ng-pon2] In the upstream direction, tunable lasers at each ONU are dynamically assigned to a wavelength.
[src:gpon-deep/ng-pon2] Fibres from all ONUs are combined with a passive mux/splitter.
[src:gpon-deep/ng-pon2] Time-division multiplexing is provided in the upstream direction through the use of burst lasers at each ONU.
[src:gpon-deep/ng-pon2] Each upstream/downstream wavelength is capable of providing up to 10 Gbit/s symmetric bandwidth to each subscriber if the channel is not time-division multiplexed between several ONUs.
[src:gpon-deep/ng-pon2] With wavelength-division multiplexing on four available wavelengths, NG-PON2 can provide up to 40 Gbit/s throughput to the entire optical network.
[src:gpon-deep/ng-pon2] Deployments for several downstream/upstream subscriber rates are described within the standard including 10/10 Gbit/s at each subscriber, 10/2.5 Gbit/s, and 2.5/2.5 Gbit/s.
[src:gpon-deep/ng-pon2] Additionally, some wavelengths are reserved for potential use in Point-to-Point applications.
[src:gpon-deep/ng-pon2] NG-PON2 was designed to include backwards-compatibility, or coexistence, with previous architectures to ease deployment into existing optical distribution networks.
[src:gpon-deep/ng-pon2] Wavelengths were specifically chosen to avoid interference with GPON, 10G-PON, RF Video, and OTDR measurements.
[src:gpon-deep/ng-pon2] The standard provides spectral flexibility to occupy reserved wavelengths in deployments devoid of legacy architectures.
[src:gpon-deep/ng-pon2] Additionally, a mux/demux used to combine and separate the NG-PON2 wavelength channels at the OLT can be designed with a coexistence element to isolate legacy wavelengths.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-line-termination] An **optical line termination** (**OLT**), also called an **optical line terminal**, is a device which serves as the service provider endpoint of a passive optical network.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-line-termination] 2. to coordinate the multiplexing between the conversion devices on the other end of that network (called either optical network terminals or optical network units).
[src:gpon-deep/optical-line-termination] In general, an OLT is akin to a network switch where each port represents one or more client ONT or a node.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-line-termination] Each port may be attached to the boards or network/line cards via a SFP module which must be a OLT module for it to have its Tx and Rx wavelengths swapped, but not all OLTs use SFP modules as shown in the image to the left.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-line-termination] OLTs are either found at the ISP level inside a cabinet or distribution point, or customer level for connecting ONTs locally, such as a hotel or apartments.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-line-termination] Depending on the underlying fiber technology, an OLT can be EPON, GPON, XG-PON or WDM.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-line-termination] XGS-PON networks support split ratios of up to 1:128.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-line-termination] An OLT with 272 ports can support up to 34,816 users assuming a split ratio of 1:128 for every port.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-line-termination] It can be located in a point of presence which can be a curb-side cabinet or building, or a central office.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-line-termination] Most vendors integrate an entire fiber optic management system for ISPs to manage OLTs as well as client ONTs and as such are not interoperable.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] In telecommunications, a **network interface device** (**NID**; also known by several other names) is a device that serves as the demarcation point between the carrier's local loop and the customer's premises wiring.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] Outdoor telephone NIDs also provide the subscriber with access to the station wiring and serve as a convenient test point for verification of loop integrity and of the subscriber's inside wiring.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] Generically, a NID may also be called a **network interface unit** (NIU), **telephone network interface** (TNI), **system network interface** (SNI), or **telephone network box**.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] Australia's National Broadband Network uses the term *network termination device* or NTD.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] A **smartjack** is a type of NID with capabilities beyond simple electrical connection, such as diagnostics.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] An **optical network terminal** (ONT) is a type of NID used with fiber-to-the-premises applications.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] The simplest NIDs are essentially just a specialized set of wiring terminals.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] These will typically take the form of a small, weather-proof box, mounted on the outside of the building.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] The telephone line from the telephone company will enter the NID and be connected to one side.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] The customer connects their wiring to the other side.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] A single NID enclosure may contain termination for a single line or multiple lines.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] In its role as the demarcation point (dividing line), the NID separates the telephone company's equipment from the customer's wiring and equipment.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] The telephone company owns the NID and all wiring up to it.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] Anything past the NID is the customer's responsibility.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] To facilitate this, there is typically a test jack inside the NID.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] Accessing the test jack disconnects the customer premises wiring from the public switched telephone network and allows the customer to plug a "known good" telephone into the jack to isolate trouble.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] If the telephone works at the test jack, the problem is the customer's wiring, and the customer is responsible for repair.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] If the telephone does not work, the line is faulty and the telephone company is responsible for repair.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] Most NIDs also include "circuit protectors", which are surge protectors for a telephone line.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] They protect customer wiring, equipment, and personnel from any transient energy on the line, such as from a lightning strike to a utility pole.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] Simple NIDs are "dumb" devices, as they contain no digital logic.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] They have no capabilities beyond wiring termination, circuit protection, and providing a place to connect test equipment.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] Several types of NIDs provide more than just a terminal for the connection of wiring.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] Such NIDs are colloquially called *smartjacks* or Intelligent Network Interface Devices (INIDs) as an indication of their built-in "intelligence", as opposed to a simple NID, which is just a wiring device.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] Smartjacks are typically used for more complicated types of telecommunications service, such as T1 lines.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] Plain old telephone service lines generally cannot be equipped with smartjacks.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] Despite the name, most smartjacks are much more than a simple telephone jack.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] One common form for a smartjack is a printed circuit board with a face plate on one edge, mounted in an enclosure.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] A smartjack may provide signal conversion, converting codes and protocols, *e.g.*, framing types, to the type needed by the customer equipment.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] It may buffer and/or regenerate the signal, to compensate for signal degradation from line transmission, similar to what a repeater does.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] Smartjacks also typically provide diagnostic capabilities.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] A very common capability provided by a smartjack is loopback, such that the signal from the telephone company is transmitted back to the telephone company.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] This allows the company to test the line from the central telephone exchange, without the need to have test equipment at the customer site.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] The telephone company usually has the ability to remotely activate loopback, without even needing personnel at the customer site.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] When looped back, the customer equipment is disconnected from the line.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] Additional smartjack diagnostic capabilities include alarm indication signal, which reports trouble at one end of the line to the far end.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] This helps the telephone company know if trouble is present in the line, the smartjack, or customer equipment.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] Indicator lights to show configuration, status, and alarms are also common.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] Smartjacks typically derive their operating power from the telephone line, rather than relying on premises electrical power, although this is not a universal rule.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] In fiber-to-the-premises systems, the signal is transmitted to the customer premises using optical fiber technologies.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] Unlike many conventional telephone technologies, this does not provide power for premises equipment, nor is it suitable for direct connection to customer equipment.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] If the device combines all these services into one it is known as an IAD.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] As the ONT must derive its power from the customer premises electrical supply, many ONTs have the option for a battery backup in order to maintain service in the event of a power outage or it will go in alarm mode if disconnected and customer may be notified of this.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] These terminals are used in both active optical networks and passive optical networks.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] Typically, an ONT connects via a fiber-optic cable to an OLT to complete a connection.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] An ONT can work in Single Family Unit/SFU mode (modem/bridge) or Home Gateway Unit/HGU mode (router).
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] In passive optical networks, Management is provided by the OLT via OMCI, in case of a GPON connection, and OAM in case of a EPON connection.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] Authentication and encryption is done via LOID for EPON and PLOAM password, GPON serial number or others for GPON.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] Severe climatic conditions: These cover environments more severe than those of a normal environment (i.e., higher humidity, high lightning activity, exposure to salt-laden atmosphere, and exposure to contaminants).
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] Temperatures are expected to be in the range of −40 to 43 °C (−40 to 109 °F), and humidity may exceed 90% RH.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] Jacks installed in NIDs in such environments are known to become contaminated and develop low insulation resistances and low dielectric breakdown voltages when subjected to high humidity.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] These problems can cause noisy lines or even service outages.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] Flooded conditions: These cover areas of a service provider prone to flooding, such as in coastal or flood plain locations.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] After a flooding incident, temperature is expected to be in the range of 4.5 to 38 °C (40 to 100 °F), and humidity may exceed 90% RH.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] The requirements are not to determine if the NID will function during a flood, but to review the ability of the NID to function after the flood has subsided.
[src:gpon-deep/optical-network-unit] Service providers must decide which condition best suits their application.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] A **passive optical network** (**PON**) is a fiber-optic telecommunications network that uses only *unpowered* devices to carry signals, as opposed to electronic equipment.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] In practice, PONs are typically used for the *last mile* between Internet service providers (ISP) and their customers.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] In this use, a PON has a point-to-multipoint topology in which an ISP uses a single device to serve many end-user sites using a system such as 10G-PON or GPON.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] In this one-to-many topology, a single fiber serving many sites branches into multiple fibers through a passive splitter, and those fibers can each serve multiple sites through further splitters.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] The light from the ISP is divided through the splitters to reach all the customer sites, and light from the customer sites is combined into the single fiber.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] A passive optical network consists of an optical line terminal (OLT) at the service provider's central office (hub), passive (non-power-consuming) optical splitters, and a number of optical network units (ONUs) or optical network terminals (ONTs), which are near end users.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] There may be amplifiers between the OLT and the ONUs.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Several fibers from an OLT can be carried in a single cable.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] A PON reduces the amount of fiber and central office equipment required compared with point-to-point architectures with dedicated connections for every user.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] A passive optical network is a form of fiber-optic access network.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Bandwidth is commonly shared among users of a PON.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] In most cases, downstream signals are broadcast to all premises sharing multiple fibers.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Upstream signals are combined using a multiple access protocol, usually time-division multiple access (TDMA).
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Passive optical networks were first proposed by British Telecommunications in 1987.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Two major standard groups, the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) and the Telecommunication Standardization Sector of the International Telecommunication Union (ITU-T), develop standards along with a number of other industry organizations.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] The Society of Cable Telecommunications Engineers (SCTE) also specified radio frequency over glass for carrying signals over a passive optical network.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] CableLabs has developed coherent PON (CPON) that runs at 100 Gbit/s symmetrically and supports split ratios of up to 1:512.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Coherent means it only needs a single wavelength of light to operate.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Starting in 1995, work on fiber to the home architectures was done by the Full Service Access Network (FSAN) working group, formed by major telecommunications service providers and system vendors.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] The International Telecommunication Union (ITU) did further work, and standardized on two generations of PON.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] The older ITU-T G.983 standard was based on Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM), and has therefore been referred to as APON (ATM PON).
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Further improvements to the original APON standard – as well as the gradual falling out of favor of ATM as a protocol – led to the full, final version of ITU-T G.983 being referred to more often as *broadband* PON, or BPON.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] A typical APON/BPON provides 622 megabits per second (Mbit/s) (OC-12) of downstream bandwidth and 155 Mbit/s (OC-3) of upstream traffic, although the standard accommodates higher rates.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] The ITU-T G.984 *Gigabit-capable Passive Optical Networks* (GPON, G-PON) standard, first defined in 2003, represented an increase, compared to BPON, in both the total bandwidth and bandwidth efficiency through the use of larger, variable-length packets.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Again, the standards permit several choices of bit rate, but the industry has converged on 2.488 gigabits per second (Gbit/s) of downstream bandwidth, and 1.244 Gbit/s of upstream bandwidth.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] GPON Encapsulation Method (GEM) allows very efficient packaging of user traffic with frame segmentation.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] By mid-2008, Verizon had installed over 800000 lines.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] British Telecom, BSNL, Saudi Telecom Company, Etisalat, and AT&T were in advanced trials in Britain, India, Saudi Arabia, the UAE, and the US, respectively.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] GPON networks have now been deployed in numerous networks across the globe, and the trends indicate higher growth in GPON than other PON technologies.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] G.987 defined 10G-PON in 2010 with 10 Gbit/s downstream and 2.5 Gbit/s upstream – framing is "G-PON like" and designed to coexist with GPON devices on the same network.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Asymmetrical 50G-PON was approved by the ITU in September 2021, and symmetrical 50G-PON was approved in September 2022.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] The first trial of 50G-PON took place in 2024 in Turkey.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] 100G-PON and 200G-PON have been demonstrated.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] The first demonstration of 100G-PON in a live network was done in Australia in 2024.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Developed in 2009 by Cable Manufacturing Business to meet SIPRNet requirements of the U.S.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Air Force, secure passive optical network (SPON) integrates gigabit passive optical network (GPON) technology and protective distribution system (PDS).
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Changes to the NSTISSI 7003 requirements for PDS and the mandate by the US federal government for GREEN technologies allowed for the US federal government consideration of the two technologies as an alternative to active Ethernet and encryption devices.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] The chief information officer of the United States Department of the Army issued a directive to adopt the technology by fiscal year 2013.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] It is marketed to the US military by companies such as Telos Corporation.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] GPON used in Fiber to the x deployments may face vulnerability to Denial-of-service attack via optical signal injections, unresolved based on current commercially available technologies.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] In 2004, the Ethernet PON (EPON or GEPON) standard 802.3ah-2004 was ratified as part of the Ethernet in the first mile project of the IEEE 802.3.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] EPON is a "short haul" network using Ethernet packets, fiber optic cables, and single protocol layer.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] EPON also uses standard 802.3 Ethernet frames with symmetric 1 gigabit per second upstream and downstream rates.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] EPON is applicable for data-centric networks, as well as full-service voice, data and video networks.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] 10 Gbit/s EPON or 10G-EPON was ratified as an amendment IEEE 802.3av to IEEE 802.3.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] The downstream wavelength plan support simultaneous operation of 10 Gbit/s on one wavelength and 1 Gbit/s on a separate wavelength for the operation of IEEE 802.3av and IEEE 802.3ah on the same PON concurrently.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] The upstream channel can support simultaneous operation of IEEE 802.3av and 1 Gbit/s 802.3ah simultaneously on a single shared (1310 nm) channel.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] In 2014, there were over 40 million installed EPON ports, making it the most widely deployed PON technology globally.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] EPON is also the foundation for cable operators' business services as part of the DOCSIS Provisioning of EPON (DPoE) specifications.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] 10G EPON is fully compatible with other Ethernet standards and requires no conversion or encapsulation to connect to Ethernet-based networks on either the upstream or downstream end.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] This technology connects seamlessly with any type of IP-based or packetized communications, and, thanks to the ubiquity of Ethernet installations in homes, workplaces, and elsewhere, EPON is generally very inexpensive to implement.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] A PON takes advantage of wavelength-division multiplexing (WDM), using one wavelength for downstream traffic and another for upstream traffic on a single mode fiber (ITU-T G.652, typically OS2).
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] BPON, EPON, GEPON, and GPON have the same basic wavelength plan and use the 1490 nanometer (nm) wavelength for downstream traffic and 1310 nm wavelength for upstream traffic.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] 1550 nm is reserved for optional overlay services, typically RF (analog) video.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] As with bit rate, the standards describe several optical power budgets, most common is 28 dB of loss budget for both BPON and GPON, but products have been announced using less expensive optics as well.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] 28 dB corresponds to about 20 km with a 32-way split.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Forward error correction (FEC) may provide for another 2–3 dB of loss budget on GPON systems.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] As optics improve, the 28 dB budget will likely increase.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Although both the GPON and EPON protocols permit large split ratios (up to 128 subscribers for GPON, up to 32,768 for EPON), in practice most PONs are deployed with a split ratio of 1:64, 1:32 or smaller.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] XGS-PON networks support split ratios of up to 1:128 and 50G-PON supports split ratios of at least 1:256 depending on the OLT.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Splitters may be cascaded, such as in areas with a low population density and thus a low number of subscribers in a given area.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] This can also be done to facilitate reducing the number of subscribers in a PON in the future.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Thus, PONs can have a tree network topology.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] In rural areas, remote OLTs with capacity for only a few users can be used.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Splitters can be made with either planar lightwave circuit (PLC) or fused biconical taper (FBT) technologies: PLC creates optical waveguides in a flat substrate made of silica to split light, and FBT fuses optical fibers together to create a splitter.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] A PON consists of a central office node, called an optical line terminal (OLT), one or more user nodes, called optical network units (ONUs) or optical network terminals (ONTs), and the fibers and splitters between them, called the optical distribution network (ODN).
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] "ONT" is an ITU-T term to describe a single-tenant ONU.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] An ONU is a device that terminates the PON and presents customer service interfaces to the user.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Some ONUs implement a separate subscriber unit to provide services such as telephony, Ethernet data, or video.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] An OLT provides the interface between a PON and a service provider's core network.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] The ONT or ONU terminates the PON and presents the native service interfaces to the user.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] A PON is a shared network, in that the OLT sends a single stream of downstream traffic that is seen by all ONUs.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Each ONU reads the content of only those packets that are addressed to it.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Encryption is used to prevent eavesdropping on downstream traffic.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] An OLT can have several ports, and each port can drive a single PON network with split ratios or splitting factors of around 1:32 or 1:64, meaning that for each port on the OLT, up to 32 or 64 ONUs at customer sites can be connected.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Several PON standards can co-exist on the same ODN (optical distribution network) by using different wavelengths.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] The OLT is responsible for allocating upstream bandwidth to the ONUs.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Because the optical distribution network (ODN) is shared, ONU upstream transmissions could collide if they were transmitted at random times.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] ONUs can lie at varying distances from the OLT, meaning that the transmission delay from each ONU is unique.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] The OLT measures delay and sets a register in each ONU via PLOAM (physical layer operations, administrations and maintenance) messages to equalize its delay with respect to all of the other ONUs on the PON.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Once the delay of all ONUs has been set, the OLT transmits so-called grants to the individual ONUs.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] A grant is permission to use a defined interval of time for upstream transmission.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] The grant map is dynamically re-calculated every few milliseconds.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] The map allocates bandwidth to all ONUs, such that each ONU receives timely bandwidth for its service needs.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Some services – POTS, for example – require essentially constant upstream bandwidth, and the OLT may provide a fixed bandwidth allocation to each such service that has been provisioned.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] DS1 and some classes of data service may also require constant upstream bit rate.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] But much data traffic, such as browsing web sites, is bursty and highly variable.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Through dynamic bandwidth allocation (DBA), a PON can be oversubscribed for upstream traffic, according to the traffic engineering concepts of statistical multiplexing.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] (Downstream traffic can also be oversubscribed, in the same way that any LAN can be oversubscribed.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] In GPON there are two forms of DBA, status-reporting (SR) and non-status reporting (NSR).
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] In NSR DBA, the OLT continuously allocates a small amount of extra bandwidth to each ONU.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] If the ONU has no traffic to send, it transmits idle frames during its excess allocation.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] If the OLT observes that a given ONU is not sending idle frames, it increases the bandwidth allocation to that ONU.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Once the ONU's burst has been transferred, the OLT observes a large number of idle frames from the given ONU, and reduces its allocation accordingly.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] NSR DBA has the advantage that it imposes no requirements on the ONU, and the disadvantage that there is no way for the OLT to know how best to assign bandwidth across several ONUs that need more.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] In SR DBA, the OLT polls ONUs for their backlogs.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] A given ONU may have several so-called transmission containers (T-CONTs), each with its own priority or traffic class.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] The ONU reports each T-CONT separately to the OLT.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] The report message contains a logarithmic measure of the backlog in the T-CONT queue.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] By knowledge of the service level agreement for each T-CONT across the entire PON, as well as the size of each T-CONT's backlog, the OLT can optimize allocation of the spare bandwidth on the PON.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] EPON systems use a DBA mechanism equivalent to GPON's SR DBA solution.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] The OLT polls ONUs for their queue status and grants bandwidth using the MPCP GATE message, while ONUs report their status using the MPCP REPORT message.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] For TDM-PON, a passive optical splitter is used in the optical distribution network.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] In the upstream direction, each ONU (optical network units) or ONT (optical network terminal) burst transmits for an assigned time-slot (multiplexed in the time domain).
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] In this way, the OLT is receiving signals from only one ONU or ONT at any point in time.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] In the downstream direction, the OLT (usually) continuously transmits (or may burst transmit).
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] ONUs or ONTs see their own data through the address labels embedded in the signal.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] APON/BPON, EPON and GPON have been widely deployed.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] In November 2014, EPON had approximately 40 million deployed ports and ranks first in deployments.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] As of 2015, GPON (gigabit) had a smaller market share, but is anticipated to reach $10.5 billion US dollars by 2020.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] XGS-PON (10 gigabit) is popular among fiber ISPs in the US as of 2022.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] In short it implements the DOCSIS Operations Administration Maintenance and Provisioning (OAMP) functionality on existing EPON equipment.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] It makes the EPON OLT look and act like a DOCSIS Cable Modem Termination Systems (CMTS) platform (which is called a DPoE System in DPoE terminology).
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] In addition to offering the same IP service capabilities as a CMTS, DPoE supports Metro Ethernet Forum (MEF) 9 and 14 services for the delivery of Ethernet services for business customers.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Comcast Xfinity and Charter Spectrum use 10G-EPON with DPoE in newly deployed areas, including new construction and rural expansion.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Radio frequency over glass (RFoG) is a type of passive optical network that transports RF signals that were formerly transported over copper (principally over a hybrid fiber-coaxial cable) over PON.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] In the forward direction RFoG is either a stand-alone P2MP system or an optical overlay for existing PON such as GEPON/EPON.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] The overlay for RFoG is based on wavelength-division multiplexing (WDM)—the passive combination of wavelengths on a single strand of glass.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Reverse RF support is provided by transporting the upstream or return RF onto a separate wavelength from the PON return wavelength.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] The Society of Cable and Telecommunications Engineers (SCTE) Interface Practices Subcommittee (IPS) Work Group 5, is currently working on IPS 910 RF over Glass.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] RFoG offers backwards compatibility with existing RF modulation technology, but offers no additional bandwidth for RF based services.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Although not yet completed, the RFoG standard is actually a collection of standardized options which are not compatible with each other (they cannot be mixed on the same PON).
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Some of the standards may interoperate with other PONs, others may not.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] It offers a means to support RF technologies in locations where only fiber is available or where copper is not permitted or feasible.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] This technology is targeted towards Cable TV operators and their existing HFC networks, but is also used by Verizon, Frontier Communications and Ziply Fiber to deliver pay TV services over fiber despite these companies never having owned or deployed a HFC network.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Wavelength-Division Multiplexing PON (WDM-PON) is a non-standard type of passive optical networking that is being developed by some companies.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] The multiple wavelengths of a WDM-PON can be used to separate Optical Network Units (ONUs) into several virtual PONs co-existing on the same physical infrastructure.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Alternatively the wavelengths can be used collectively through statistical multiplexing to provide efficient wavelength utilization and lower delays experienced by the ONUs.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] There is no common standard for WDM-PON nor any unanimously agreed upon definition of the term.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] By some definitions WDM-PON is a dedicated wavelength for each ONU.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Other more liberal definitions suggest the use of more than one wavelength in any one direction on a PON is WDM-PON.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] It is difficult to point to an un-biased list of WDM-PON vendors when there is no such unanimous definition.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] PONs provide higher bandwidth than traditional copper based access networks.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] WDM-PON has better privacy and better scalability because of each ONU only receives its own wavelength.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Time- and wavelength-division multiplexed passive optical network (TWDM-PON) is a primary solution for the next-generation passive optical network stage 2 (NG-PON2) by the full service access network (FSAN) in April 2012.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] TWDM-PON coexists with commercially deployed Gigabit PON (G-PON) and 10 Gigabit PON (XG-PON) systems.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] While G-PON, XG-PON, and XGS-PON only support one wavelength per direction, NG-PON supports 4 or 8 wavelengths per direction, and 10 Gbit/s per wavelength for up to 80 Gbit/s of downstream and upstream bandwidth.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] The concept of the Long-Reach Optical Access Network (LROAN) is to replace the optical/electrical/optical conversion that takes place at the local exchange with a continuous optical path that extends from the customer to the core of the network.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Work by Davey and Payne at BT showed that significant cost savings could be made by reducing the electronic equipment and real-estate required at the local exchange or wire center.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] A proof of concept demonstrator showed that it was possible to serve 1024 users at 10 Gbit/s with 100 km reach.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] This technology has sometimes been termed Long-Reach PON, however, many argue that the term PON is no longer applicable as, in most instances, only the distribution remains passive.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Due to the topology of PON, the transmission modes for downstream (that is, from OLT to ONU) and upstream (that is, from ONU to OLT) are different.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] For the downstream transmission, the OLT broadcasts optical signal to all the ONUs in continuous mode (CM), that is, the downstream channel always has optical data signal.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] However, in the upstream channel, ONUs can not transmit optical data signal in CM.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Use of CM would result in all of the signals transmitted from the ONUs converging (with attenuation) into one fiber by the power splitter (serving as power coupler), and overlapping.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] To solve this problem, burst mode (BM) transmission is adopted for upstream channel.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] The given ONU only transmits optical packet when it is allocated a time slot and it needs to transmit, and all the ONUs share the upstream channel in the time-division multiplexing (TDM) mode.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] The phases of the BM optical packets received by the OLT are different from packet to packet, since the ONUs are not synchronized to transmit optical packet in the same phase, and the distance between OLT and given ONU are random.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Since the distance between the OLT and ONUs are not uniform, the optical packets received by the OLT may have different amplitudes.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] In order to compensate the phase variation and amplitude variation in a short time (for example within 40 ns for GPON), burst mode clock and data recovery (BM-CDR) and burst mode amplifier (for example burst mode TIA) need to be employed, respectively.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Furthermore, the BM transmission mode requires the transmitter to work in burst mode.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Such a burst mode transmitter is able to turn on and off in short time.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] The above three kinds of circuitries in PON are quite different from their counterparts in the point-to-point continuous mode optical communication link.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Passive optical networks do not use electrically powered components to split the signal.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Instead, the signal is distributed using beam splitters.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Each splitter typically splits the signal from a single fiber into 16, 32, or up to 256 fibers, depending on the manufacturer, and several splitters can be aggregated in a single cabinet.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] A beam splitter cannot provide any switching or buffering capabilities and does not use any power supply; the resulting connection is called a point-to-multipoint link.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] For such a connection, the optical network terminals on the customer's end must perform some special functions which would not otherwise be required.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] For example, due to the absence of switching, each signal leaving the central office must be broadcast to all users served by that splitter (including to those for whom the signal is not intended).
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] It is therefore up to the optical network terminal to filter out any signals intended for other customers.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] In addition, since splitters have no buffering, each individual optical network terminal must be coordinated in a multiplexing scheme to prevent signals sent by customers from colliding with each other.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Two types of multiplexing are possible for achieving this: wavelength-division multiplexing and time-division multiplexing.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] With wavelength-division multiplexing, each customer transmits their signal using a unique wavelength.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] With time-division multiplexing (TDM), the customers "take turns" transmitting information.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] TDM equipment has been on the market longest.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Because there is no single definition of "WDM-PON" equipment, various vendors claim to have released the 'first' WDM-PON equipment, but there is no consensus on which product was the 'first' WDM-PON product to market.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Passive optical networks have both advantages and disadvantages over active networks.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] They avoid the complexities involved in keeping electronic equipment operating outdoors.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] They also allow for analog broadcasts, which can simplify the delivery of analog television.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] However, because each signal must be pushed out to *everyone* served by the splitter (rather than to just a single switching device), the central office must be equipped with a particularly powerful piece of transmitting equipment called an optical line terminal (OLT).
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Optical distribution networks can also be designed in a point-to-point "homerun" topology where splitters and/or active networking are all located at the central office, allowing users to be patched into whichever network is required from the optical distribution frame.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] The drivers behind the modern passive optical network are high reliability, low cost, and passive functionality.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Single-mode, passive optical components include branching devices such as Wavelength-Division Multiplexer/Demultiplexers (WDMs), isolators, circulators, and filters.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Proposed requirements for these components were published in 2010 by Telcordia Technologies.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] The broad variety of passive optical components applications include multichannel transmission, distribution, optical taps for monitoring, pump combiners for fiber amplifiers, bit-rate limiters, optical connects, route diversity, polarization diversity, interferometers, and coherent communication.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] WDMs are optical components in which power is split or combined based on the wavelength composition of the optical signal.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] *Dense Wavelength-Division Multiplexers (DWDMs)* are optical components that split power over at least four wavelengths.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] *Wavelength insensitive couplers* are passive optical components in which power is split or combined independently of the wavelength composition of the optical signal.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] A given component may combine and divide optical signals simultaneously, as in bidirectional (duplex) transmission over a single fiber.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Passive optical components are data format transparent, combining and dividing optical power in some predetermined ratio (*coupling ratio*) regardless of the information content of the signals.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] WDMs can be thought of as *wavelength* splitters and combiners.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Wavelength insensitive couplers can be thought of as *power* splitters and combiners.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] An optical *isolator* is a two-port passive component that allows light (in a given wavelength range) to pass through with low attenuation in one direction, while isolating (providing a high attenuation for) light propagating in the reverse direction.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Isolators are used as both integral and in-line components in laser diode modules and optical amplifiers, and to reduce noise caused by multi-path reflection in high-bitrate and analog transmission systems.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] An optical *circulator* operates in a similar way to an optical isolator, except that the reverse propagating lightwave is directed to a third port for output, instead of being lost.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] An optical circulator can be used for bidirectional transmission, as a type of branching component that distributes (and isolates) optical power among fibers, based on the direction of the lightwave propagation.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] A fiber optic *filter* is a component with two or more ports that provides wavelength sensitive loss, isolation and/or return loss.
[src:gpon-deep/passive-optical-network] Fiber optic filters are in-line, wavelength selective, components that allow a specific range of wavelengths to pass through (or reflect) with low attenuation for classification of filter types.
